It seems like the issue here is that can_software_clip_entry blindly assumes that all entries in the clip stack are rectangles. We already check the scissor clip bounds above in the loop, and the other user of can_software_clip_entry also bails if we have a non-world-space clip, so all that should be needed is a:

```cpp
    if (clip_entry->type == COGL_CLIP_STACK_WINDOW_RECT)
      continue;
```

Right at the beginning of the clip stack iteration loop in can_software_clip_entry. And then you should be able to remove the `can_software_clip = FALSE;` there.

This does not appear to be working. In my application, I have the following snippet:

```c
#if 1
		{
			//GtkCssProvider *css_provider;
			gchar *font, *css, *view;
			PangoFontDescription *desc;

			font = g_settings_get_string(app->settings,
						     "viewer-font");
			desc = pango_font_description_from_string(font);
			g_free(font);
			css = pango_font_description_to_css(desc);
			debug("Font CSS: textview %s", css);
			view = g_strdup_printf("textview %s", css);
			g_free(css);
			gtk_css_provider_load_from_data(app->css, view, -1,
							NULL);
		}
#endif
```
The function pango_font_description_to_css() has been taken from [https://source.puri.sm/dorota.czaplejewicz/gtk/commit/99c2423043f0c95a60093c618e00823e42e0ddfa](https://source.puri.sm/dorota.czaplejewicz/gtk/commit/99c2423043f0c95a60093c618e00823e42e0ddfa) since I could not find anything already existing in Gtk/Pango that does this.

app->css is created in the following way:

```c
	app->css = gtk_css_provider_new();
	gtk_css_provider_load_from_resource(
		app->css, "/org/gtk/gtkscope/css/default.css");
	gtk_style_context_add_provider_for_screen(
		screen, GTK_STYLE_PROVIDER(app->css),
		GTK_STYLE_PROVIDER_PRIORITY_APPLICATION);
```

When I change the font, the debug print produces the following output:

```
AppWindow :: [window.c:719] Font CSS: textview { font-family: Sans; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 8pt}
```

However, the size of the GtkSourceView **and** GtkSourceMap both get changed to the same thing. So, either there really is a bug or the above description is missing something detail. The documentation for GtkSourceMap does not mention any specific CSS selectors that could be used to modify the size used by GtkSourceMap, itself.

Actually, it appears that there is a way to do this through CSS without dealing with individual widgets:

```css
textview.sourceview { ... }
textview.monospace.sourceview { ... }
```
appears to do the trick.
